        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-12-08T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-12-08T08:00:00-05:00" n="548"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d548">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 P. W./741: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-12-08T08:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 8, 1941—8 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5743. From the President. Your 5929, December 7 [<hi rend="italic">8</hi>], 4
                    p.m. [<hi rend="italic">a.m.</hi>] “I think it best on account of psychology
                    here that formal <pb facs="0741" n="733" xml:id="pg_733"/> British declaration
                    of war be withheld until after my speech<note n="8" xml:id="d548fn8">For text of
                        President Roosevelt’s message to Congress on December 8, see <ref
                            target="frus1931-41v02#pg_793">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 793</ref>.</note> at 12:30 Washington
                    time. I am asking for declaration.<note n="9" xml:id="d548fn9">For the
                        declaration of a state of war with Japan, see <ref
                            target="frus1931-41v02#pg_795">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, p. 795</ref>.</note> Any time after that
                    would be wholly satisfactory.<note n="10" xml:id="d548fn10">British Prime
                        Minister Churchill made his statement to the House of Commons at 3 p.m.,
                        London time (10 a.m., Washington time), December 8; for text, see United
                        Kingdom, <hi rend="italic">Parliamentary Debates</hi>, House of Commons, 5th
                        series, vol. 376, p. 1358.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Delighted to know of message to de Valera. Roosevelt.”</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
